# Deploying College-ERP on Azure Kubernetes Service (AKS)
This guide walks through deploying the College-ERP application on AKS using an Azure Container Registry (ACR) image.
1. Login to Azure
az login

2. Check Azure Container Service Provider Registration
az provider show --namespace Microsoft.ContainerService --query registrationState
If it returns "Registered", you can skip registration. Otherwise:
az provider register --namespace Microsoft.ContainerService
Verify registration:
az provider show --namespace Microsoft.ContainerService --query registrationState

3. Set Up Environment Variables
Generate a random ID for unique resource names:
export RANDOM_ID="$(openssl rand -hex 3)"
export MY_RESOURCE_GROUP_NAME="college-erp$RANDOM_ID"
export REGION="centralus"
export MY_AKS_CLUSTER_NAME="college-erp$RANDOM_ID"
export MY_DNS_LABEL="mydnslabel$RANDOM_ID"

echo $RANDOM_ID

4. Create Azure Resource Group
az group create --name $MY_RESOURCE_GROUP_NAME --location $REGION

5. Create AKS Cluster
az aks create \
  --resource-group $MY_RESOURCE_GROUP_NAME \
  --name $MY_AKS_CLUSTER_NAME \
  --node-count 1 \
  --node-vm-size Standard_D2s_v3 \
  --generate-ssh-keys

6. Configure kubectl to Connect to AKS
az aks get-credentials --resource-group $MY_RESOURCE_GROUP_NAME --name $MY_AKS_CLUSTER_NAME
kubectl get nodes

7. Create Kubernetes Image Pull Secret for ACR
Step 7.1: Verify ACR Credentials
Your ACR username and password:
az acr credential show --name collegeerp --query "username"
# Output: "collegeerp"

az acr credential show --name collegeerp --query "passwords[0].value"
# Output: "vxB45S7H303RMKYiY48piGWy1zFmvyrx40U9ecldcLa8AAK19mr8JQQJ99CAAC1i4TkEqg7NAAACAZCRbFzg"
Step 7.2: Create Kubernetes Secret
kubectl create secret docker-registry acr-secret \
  --docker-server=collegeerp.azurecr.io \
  --docker-username="collegeerp" \
  --docker-password="vxB45S7H303RMKYiY48piGWy1zFmvyrx40U9ecldcLa8AAK19mr8JQQJ99CAAC1i4TkEqg7NAAACAZCRbFzg" \
  --docker-email="pavan.nec@gmail.com"
Output should confirm:
secret/acr-secret created

8. Reference the Secret in Your Deployment YAML
Add imagePullSecrets under spec:
spec:
  containers:
    - name: college-erp-web
      image: collegeerp.azurecr.io/college-erp-web:latest
      ...
  imagePullSecrets:
    - name: acr-secret

9. Apply Kubernetes Manifests
kubectl apply -f k8s/
Ensure your manifests include Deployment, Service, PVC, and any necessary ConfigMaps or Secrets.

10. Expose Web Service with LoadBalancer
If your Service is ClusterIP, change it to LoadBalancer:
kind: Service
apiVersion: v1
metadata:
  name: college-erp-web
spec:
  type: LoadBalancer
  selector:
    app: college-erp-web
  ports:
    - protocol: TCP
      port: 80
      targetPort: 8080
Apply changes:
kubectl apply -f web-service.yaml
kubectl get svc college-erp-web
Use the external IP to access your application.
